{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596875"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:18:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:18:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15418"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15418"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8109"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61345"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19670"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA liver biopsy specimen shows hepatocytes that appear swollen with pale, watery-looking cytoplasm, consistent with ballooning degeneration. This finding is commonly seen in acute viral hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism causing hepatocyte ballooning degeneration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disruption of ion pumps causing fluid accumulation","Breakdown of cell membrane phospholipids","Migration of inflammatory mediators","Accumulation of triglyceride droplets","Formation of cytoplasmic inclusions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of ballooning degeneration is \u003Cstrong\u003Edisruption of ion pumps causing fluid accumulation\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because viral infection impairs cellular energy metabolism, leading to ATP depletion and dysfunction of membrane ion pumps. The result is cellular swelling with pale, rarefied cytoplasm visible on microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakdown of cell membrane phospholipids\u003C/strong\u003E - While membrane damage can occur, pump failure is the key mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigration of inflammatory mediators\u003C/strong\u003E - While inflammation occurs in hepatitis, it does not directly cause ballooning\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of triglyceride droplets\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes steatosis, which has a different microscopic appearance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of cytoplasmic inclusions\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes features like Mallory bodies, not ballooning degeneration\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe disruption of cellular ion gradients due to ATP depletion is the key mechanism leading to fluid accumulation and the characteristic ballooned appearance of hepatocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ballooning degeneration in hepatitis occurs when ATP depletion causes sodium-potassium pump failure, leading to cellular swelling","Hepatocyte ballooning appears microscopically as enlarged cells with pale, watery cytoplasm","The sodium-potassium pump requires ATP to maintain cellular ion gradients and prevent fluid accumulation"],"references":["Lackner C, Gogg-Kamerer M, Zatloukal K, Stumptner C, Brunt EM, Denk H. Ballooned hepatocytes in steatohepatitis: the value of keratin immunohistochemistry for diagnosis. J Hepatol. 2008 May;48(5):821-8. doi: 10.1016/j.jhep.2008.01.026. Epub 2008 Feb 22. PMID: 18329127.","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61345"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15418"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61345"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T22:04:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T22:14:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8109"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75832"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"htt